{{italic title}} {{Infobox television | name = Without Pity: A Film About Abilities | image = | caption = | director = Michael Mierendorf | producer = Michael Mierendorf | executive_producer = [[Sheila Nevins]] | narrated = [[Christopher Reeve]] | writer = Michael Mierendorf | music = | editor = | company = Michael Mierendorf Productions | network = [[HBO]] | released = {{Start date|1996|10|8}} | runtime = 55 minutes | country = United States | budget = }}
'''''Without Pity: A Film About Abilities''''' is a 1996 American television [[documentary film]] narrated by [[Christopher Reeve]]. This documentary celebrates the efforts of the [[disabled]] to live full, productive lives. It originally premiered on [[HBO]] on October 8, 1996.
The viewers meet a cross section of Americans in the film. A young woman with [[cerebral palsy]] who cares for her baby, while a man with cerebral palsy lives successfully on his own after 40 years in a Colorado institution. The film takes a trip to school with a remarkable 6-year-old boy without arms or legs, visits the workplace of a [[Blindness|blind]] computer expert, and meets a professor with [[polio]] who teaches the history of discrimination against people with disabilities. A young man recently made [[paraplegic]] discusses his daily battle with [[clinical depression|depression]] and his determination and motivation to overcome it and get on with his life.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uGUlAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8qYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4463,2421529&dq=without+pity+a+film+about+abilities&hl=en|title=Reeve Narrates 'Without Pity'|date=6 Oct 1996|work=Reading Eagle|page=TV2|accessdate=29 October 2013}}</ref>
This film applauds the resilience and potential of people with disabilities and their need to be determined to be self-sufficient.
